Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden shifts in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely to occur, as the global economy remains imbalanced in many ways when emerging from the crisis, especially in terms of sovereign debts and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are at the root of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect safely and are even more difficult to prove.
Next, predicting the exact moment of the breakdown (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed, and when there is no more credit available) is, and will likely remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly nonlinear events that occur without precursor signs.
The periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those who are least responsible for them.
If this pattern were to repeat itself, it could erode confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could presage excessive regulation, state intervention, and disengagement from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is transforming into a sovereign debt crisis of advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can translate into a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration of tax revenues and an increase in bailout spending.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" of advanced economies include non-discretionary countercyclical measures.
Imbalances and undetected systemic risks mean that fiscal policies that appear prudent are in fact not so.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
But its revenues and expenses were largely determined by a housing bubble linked to very high levels of debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it undermines itself.
Greece is undoubtedly a prime example.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of liabilities through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can trigger this kind of sequential imbalance in cascades, sovereign states must be vigilant about the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk, and able to take corrective measures quickly.
New detailed legislative frameworks, focusing on capital requirements and leverage effects, transparency, ratings, and other information sources, incentives, conflicts of interest, and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection, and resolution mechanisms, are set to be adopted soon.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
But this will in no way solve the problem of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and indicative of instability.
In addition to and in complement of new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
However, some leading politicians and analysts believe that such a system, aimed at identifying and mitigating systemic risks, is futile.
The incomplete models of risk dynamics and a globally complex and permanently transforming financial system make it, according to them, either impossible or so prone to error that the effort would be unproductive for detecting risks.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are right, we then have to accept that we will periodically find ourselves in a situation of financial and fiscal instability that we cannot predict in advance.
We should then also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than we deemed necessary just three years ago.
In the domain of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists of rejecting a true proposition and the other is accepting a false proposition.
Let's call the RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be phrased this way: within the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors is likely to have the highest cost?
The opponents of prudent systemic risk surveillance have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable indicator of an increasing potential instability.
Looking for such a sign is a waste of time.
The instability occurs instantly.
But this position seems fallacious.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note.
However, it must be admitted that these warnings may not have been sufficient to be irrefutable, and they certainly did not anticipate the point of no return.
However, there were undoubtedly signs.
The second point is that while there are many indicators, they are so unreliable that taking action would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that AQF has a likely higher cost than RQV, because there are many positive factors that are false and/or that the remedy is worse than the problem.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with AQF errors.
But RQV is also expensive, as we have seen, so the aggregate negative effect of a false positive reaction (FPR) must be significant to be convincing.
I am not convinced, for my part.
There might be a deeper trend toward openness.
Whether in business or investments, choices are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty, and errors are frequent.
The default position of the decision-makers of advanced countries seems to be the opposite: that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply ingrained belief that financial markets are stable and regulate themselves.
If one thinks that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refuse to act unless one has good reasons to do so.
But in the light of past experiences, the notion that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at the very least questionable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop, and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try the experiment and give this task to a new institution, or an existing one, that has access to relevant information, possesses sharp analytical skills both in financial and macroeconomic terms, and is relatively insulated from conflicts of interest.
His analysis should be made public and could thus influence perceptions of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the system's financial ability to regulate itself.
